This is still an issue.  A misbehaving NaCl process can still cause the renderer process to be non-responsive and Chromium will eventually offer to kill the renderer process.

We *could* change the startup protocol between the trusted plugin and the IRT such that the IRT imc_accept()s the connection before transferring control to the user executable.  However, there is little point in doing that given that PPAPI's PPP_InitializeModule() and PPP_Instance/DidCreate() are currently synchronous and also block the renderer process (despite all the work in changing other interfaces to be asynchronous).
